<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / Delors: I'm no Socialist miracle worker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Without their acclaimed emperor, the French Socialist party has few clothes.
Mr Jacques Delors' dramatic decision to end weeks of mounting suspense by
announcing on prime-time television last night that he would not be their
candidate for the presidency has left the Socialists looking pretty naked.
Before last night's announcement, some in the party who had predicted the
European Commission president's answer would be no were already regretting
that he felt compelled to give it so soon. One Socialist MP had appealed to
Mr Delors not to accelerate the timetable of his answer so as 'not to
shorten the suffering of the right'.
But while the right may have last night breathed a collective sigh of relief
at seeing the front-runner in the opinion polls rule himself out of the race
for the Elysee, it knows it now faces a different kind of suffering - that
of increased civil war between rival conservatives for a prize that looks to
be within each one's grasp.
Mr Delors would himself have clearly liked to postpone announcing his
decision. Even last night, he insisted on talking about the European Union's
just-concluded Essen summit for 40 minutes before answering no to the only
question his listeners were interested in. He went on to explain that, in
addition to the personal and family reasons for wanting a break after 10
years running the Commission, he was 'no miracle doctor'. Even if he managed
to somehow levitate into the Elysee, he could not carry Socialist fortunes
high enough with him to win a leftwing majority in new parliamentary
elections.
Some leading Socialists last night put a brave face on their misfortune. Ms
Segolene Royal, a former environment minister, claimed that Mr Delors'
standing in the polls - ahead of Prime Minister Edouard Balladur as well as
Mr Jacques Chirac, mayor of Paris - 'shows the right is in a minority' in
the country. Mr Henri Emmanuelli, leader of the party since the June ousting
of Mr Michel Rocard, called on the party to take heart and promised a party
congress in January to designate its presidential candidate.
But the party could then fall to its traditional factional feuding, in
contrast to its congress last month when all rallied around an appeal to Mr
Delors to run for president.
One particular Socialist fear is that Mr Bernard Tapie may leap into the
void left by Mr Delors. Mr Tapie's political label is that of the Radical
party, a small traditional ally of the Socialists. But Mr Tapie, who said
last night 'Jacques Delors's ideas are shared by a majority of French', has
proven voter appeal among the young and working class. He might see a
presidential bid as way out of the tax and bankruptcy litigation in which he
is mired. Mr Emmanuelli reacted by warning Mr Tapie that the left needed a
candidate who could at least come second in the first round of voting on
April 23 and therefore make it into the May 7 run-off.
Causing immediate jubilation on the right last night was precisely this
prospect that for the first time since 1969, the May 7 run-off will be
between two of its own. This will cheer up Mr Chirac. The mayor of Paris
still trails Mr Balladur despite having formally opened his campaign, but
can now hope to come in second on April 23. But a close supporter of Mr
Balladur reacted with the argument that the prime minister's appeal to
centrists - particularly within his coalition partner of the UDF - made him
the best candidate, since 'Jacques Delors has abandoned the centre, and that
is where the presidential battle will be fought out'.
</TEXT>
