<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / Kinkel facing pressure to quit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GERA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Klaus Kinkel, leader of Germany's Free Democrats since 1992 and foreign
minister in Chancellor Helmut Kohl's coalition government, was last night
facing mounting pressure to resign following a hostile reception by
delegates attending a special party meeting in Gera in the eastern state of
Thuringia. The party's presidium is expected to meet in emergency session
early this morning to decide whether it would ask for Mr Kinkel's
resignation. 'He is under extreme pressure to resign. That is no surprise
given the string of electoral defeats,' said Ms Irmgard Schwaetzer, the
former construction minister. 'He will sleep on it tonight. But we should
know tomorrow if Kinkel will stay or resign.' Senior party members confirmed
that Mr Wolfgang Gerhardt, party leader of Hesse, was a possible successor
to Mr Kinkel.
Delegates at the congress repeatedly interrupted Mr Kinkel's hour-long
keynote speech with boos and whistles. The address was aimed at restoring
the party's confidence after it failed to get re-elected to nine state
parliaments over the past two years, did not enter the European Parliament
and only scraped back into the Bundestag, in October through tactical voting
by Christian Democrats.
</TEXT>
