<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 94 / Orange County starts action against banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Orange County, the beleaguered southern California district facing Dollars
1.5bn (Pounds 958m) of investment losses, formally started legal action
yesterday against a number of Wall Street investment banks.
The move came as a new team took up the task of sorting out the county's
finances, cast into chaos by the losses and a decision to file for
bankruptcy earlier this week.
Mr Thomas Hayes, a former auditor general of California and a close
associate of Mr Pete Wilson, the state's governor, was appointed late on
Thursday to lead the restructuring of the troubled investment portfolio in
order to reduce the actual losses born by the prosperous area's taxpayers.
The county also named Salomon Brothers, one of a small number of US
investment banks not to have had dealings with the investment fund, as an
adviser.
The decision to take legal action, reached after a meeting of the county's
board of supervisors on Thursday evening, will pit the county against a
number of leading firms on Wall Street, among them Morgan Stanley, Smith
Barney, Prudential Securities and Nomura. Since the filing, the firms have
all sold securities they held as collateral for loans made to the county.
Total sales had reached Dollars 11.4bn by yesterday, the county said.
Officials in California have argued that the filing put a legal block on the
firms selling the securities, a move intended to prevent its investment
losses from being realised.
'We are outraged that some broker-dealers have elected to ignore the law and
have only contributed to the uncertainty that has confronted us in recent
days,' said Mr Thomas Riley, chairman of the board of supervisors. According
to the county's lawyer, Mr Bruce Bennett of Stutman Treister &amp; Glatt, the
bankruptcy filing put an 'automatic stay' on any actions that could impair
the authority's finances.
Merrill Lynch, which had lent Dollars 2bn to the investment fund, is
believed to be the only bank not to have sold its collateral by late
yesterday.
The bankruptcy was precipitated after CS First Boston earlier this week sold
Dollars 2.6bn of securities it held belonging to the county, which is
believed to have missed an interest payment due to the bank on advances it
had made under so-called 'repurchase agreements'. CS First Boston would only
say it had 'liquidated the collateral under the terms of the agreements we
had', and that the sales had taken place before the bankruptcy filing.
Meanwhile the Securities and Exchange Commission, which regulates the US
investment markets, has moved fast with its own investigation. Merrill
Lynch, which is believed to have sold the county many of the investments on
which it faces losses, confirmed it had received a subpoena from the agency
for information. Other investment banks are understood to have received
similar requests.
See Editorial Comment, World Stock Markets and Lex
</TEXT>
