<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 94 / Weekend Money: Learning how to get poor, fast - Serious
Money
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN O'CONNOR, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
What a week of shocks. Fuel tax, VSEL, Warburg and Magellan. Magellan? In
between the big quakes came a small announcement from America: Magellan Fund
is skipping its year-end payment to its 3m investors.
So what? Well, all's well that ends well: just a minor accounting glitch -
apparently. But, for a brief few hours, the markets were full of rumours
that selling by Magellan was going to torpedo share prices round the world.
Magellan is a mutual fund - the American equivalent of a unit trust. But it
is not just any old mutual fund: it is the mutual fund equivalent of General
Motors - and when Magellan sneezes, world markets catch cold.
This is not just because Magellan is big: its assets total around Dollars
36bn. It is because its performance over many years gave the lie to those
who reckon that no fund manager can continue to beat the market.
From 1977 to 1990, the fund was run virtually single-handed by Peter Lynch.
When he moved in, it was worth Dollars 18m; when he retired, it was worth
Dollars 14bn. Anyone investing in Magellan when Lynch took over would have
been nearly 30 times richer by the time he retired. And although growth had
begun to slow even before Lynch left, the myth of the unbeatable fund
remained.
Lynch's approach to investment appeals to personal investors partly because
it sounds so easy to emulate themselves. Indeed, he has written a couple of
books explaining how the plain man can beat the professionals*.
One of the more ironic aspects of this week's rumours was the suggestion
that massive losses on derivatives were behind the skipped pay-out to
investors. Lynch himself argued vehemently that picking stocks was enough
for any red-blooded investor:
'I've never bought a future nor an option in my entire investing career, and
I can't imagine buying one now. It's hard enough to make money in regular
stocks without getting distracted by these side bets, which I'm told are
nearly impossible to win unless you are a professional trader.
' . . . If this is sensible investing, then the Titanic was a tight ship . .
. The large potential return is attractive to many small investors who are
dissatisfied with getting rich slow. Instead, they opt for getting poor
quick.'
Not, of course, that it is just small investors who take the fast lane to
penury. One reason rumour-mongers were so ready to pin derivative upsets on
to Magellan was that losses on derivatives and other highly leveraged
investments have been making the headlines with such regularity.
This week, for instance, Bankers Trust, one of Wall Street's premier
investment banks, had to sign a written agreement to make its derivatives
salesmen behave better. On the other side of the continent, a Californian
county has gone bankrupt - or tried to - because another sophisticated
financial toy exploded in its face.
Both the woes of Bankers Trust's customers and the wrangles over Orange
County's losses come back to the same thing: investors dissatisfied with
getting rich slow who learn how to get poor - fast.
To shoot oneself in one foot might be regarded as a misfortune. To shoot
oneself in both looks like carelessness. Great Universal Stores' Pounds 300m
special dividend payment has a careless tinge to it.
The market had been hoping the group would use part of its Pounds 1.5bn
excess cash to buy back some of its outstanding shares, which improves the
earnings capacity of the remaining shares. Instead, it is handing out 30p a
share to all shareholders as a special dividend - which slightly reduces
future earnings potential. That is bullet-through-foot number one: long-term
shareholder value.
But perhaps the deal has benefited shareholders in the short term? The
explanation by GUS for choosing a cash repayment rather than a buy-back was
that it was fairer to individual shareholders, since only professional
investors can normally sell shares in a buy-back. Well, up to a point, Lord
Wolfson.
The market was so disappointed by the announcement of the 30p a share
hand-out that the share price dropped 36p. Any investor paying 40 per cent
tax will have to pay another 7.5p tax on the 30p net dividend, and so ends
up with only 22.5p in the hand: notably less than the 36p fall in the share
price. Sounds like a double whammy.
*One up on Wall Street (Penguin) and Beating the Street (Simon &amp; Schuster,
New York). Both by Peter Lynch, in conjunction with John Rothchild.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
