<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 94 / Weekend Money: Finance Week
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS
Chancellor Kenneth Clarke turned to smokers, motorists and drinkers in a
mini-Budget designed to plug the gap in the government's finances caused by
the Commons' rejection of a further increase in VAT on domestic fuel.
The government moved swiftly to hold the confidence of financial markets in
the wake of its VAT defeat by pushing up interest rates 0.5 points to 6.25
per cent.
Less than an hour after Clarke stood up to deliver his mini-Budget, Northern
Rock became the first mortgage lender to announce a rise in its home loan
rate.
Companies could be forced to secure shareholder approval for executive
salary awards under proposals to be considered by a cabinet committee next
week.
The Queen is to allow oil exploration in the grounds of Windsor Castle.
Experts believe there could be up to 100m barrels, worth about Pounds 1bn,
300m below the castle.
Fifty dissatisfied customers started court proceedings against Hoover, the
electrical group, over the company's free flights offer.
Demand for credit among UK consumers eased slightly in October although it
continued to run at a high level.
Local authorities in England and Wales have detected Pounds 34m worth of
fraud in the past financial year - Pounds 9m more than 1992-93, according to
the Audit Commission.
Equalising the state pension age at 65 will cost women between 20 and 44 an
average of Pounds 14,756 each, according to the Trades Union Congress.
The stock exchange is pressing ahead with proposals to halt trading in
individual companies' shares if there is evidence that price-sensitive
information has leaked.
A teddy bear from the late Lt Col Bob Henderson's collection of 500 was sold
at Christie's in London for Pounds 110,000, double the previous world
record.
COMPANIES
SG Warburg, the largest UK investment bank, announced that it intended to
give up its independence by merging with the US investment bank Morgan
Stanley in an effort to create a stronger global bank. The news set alight
trading in the merchant bank sector.
Mercury Communications, British Telecommunications' largest competitor in
the UK, will cut 2,500 jobs, nearly a quarter of its workforce, over the
next 12 months and withdraw loss-making services - including its public
payphones - in an attempt to return to profits.
The Anglo-French company GEC Alsthom has beaten the Swedish/Swiss-owned ABB
Transportation to win an Pounds 800m to Pounds 900m order for new trains on
the London Underground.
Morgan Grenfell Investment Management was fined Pounds 180,000 by Imro, the
fund management self-regulatory body, in connection with losses from pension
schemes controlled by the late Robert Maxwell.
Brisk profits growth at Holiday Inn, the global hotel chain, allowed Bass to
report a 9 per cent rise in full-year pre-tax profits despite a further fall
in beer profits and sluggish performances from pubs and leisure.
Graeme Bowler, chief executive of grocery discounter Kwik Save since July
1993, was paid a total of Pounds 586,000 in his first year - 72 per cent
more than his predecessor, Graeme Seabrook, received in his final nine
months with the company.
Great Universal Stores, the mail order, retail, property and financial
services group, is to hand Pounds 300m of its Pounds 1.5bn cash pile back to
shareholders in the form of a 30p a share special dividend. But with the
special dividend payable only to those holding shares on Thursday, and lower
than expected profits, GUS shares fell 35p to 496p.
The acquisition of Scandinavian Leisure Group last April helped Airtours to
boost profits by 66 per cent and sales by almost the same amount.
A strong first-time contribution from the Chef &amp; Brewer pubs chain helped
Scottish &amp; Newcastle, the beer and leisure group, report a 28 per cent rise
in interim pre-tax profits from Pounds 114m to Pounds 145m.
Racal Electronics' share price fell 6 per cent on Thursday after the company
revealed it would fall short of its stated target for profits from its data
communications division this
year.
The administrators to Polly Peck International, part of the collapsed
business empire of fugitive businessman Asil Nadir, announced a breakthrough
in settling the claims of creditors. An interim payment is likely to be made
to up to 1,500 creditors by early summer.
Shares in NFC, the UK's largest transport and logistics group, fell on
Tuesday after it revealed a fall in full-year operating profits because of
losses in European logistics and a declining contribution from removal
services.
Fidelity Investments' Magellan fund, the biggest mutual fund in the US, said
it would not make a year-end distribution to its 3m investors - the first
time it has not made a year-end cash payment since 1988.
Bryan Townsend, chief executive of Midlands Electricity, said he did not
expect an announcement on the flotation of the National Grid until after
mid-January.
National Westminster Bank is planning to open several branches over the
coming Sundays to take advantage of the pre-Christmas shopping rush.
Stagecoach Holdings, the UK's largest bus group, announced a 64 per cent
rise in pre-tax profits.
Trade and industry secretary Michael Heseltine referred bids from both
British Aerospace and GEC for the submarine maker VSEL to the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission. The decision surprised the City, which was confident
both bids would be cleared, and VSEL's share price fell sharply.
MARKETS
The UK equity market on Wednesday successfully rode out what, potentially,
was one of the most turbulent trading sessions in recent months. This was in
spite of the serious defeat of the government over VAT in the House of
Commons the night before, a rise of  1/2 percentage point in domestic
interest rates, a Pounds 2bn gilts auction, and a warning of possible
further US interest rate increases in the short term.
Hong Kong closed at a 14-month low on Thursday as the spectre of rising US
interest rates continued to undermine sentiment.
Gilts were whipped around by political worries but they rallied sharply on
the Bank of England's unexpectedly early announcement that it was raising
its minimum lending rate. They were bolstered further by encouraging
comments on inflation from Bank governor Eddie George.
Oil prices weakened further on Monday as unseasonably warm weather persisted
in many parts of Europe and the US. They recovered slightly later in the
week.
US share prices fell sharply late on Thursday afternoon amid renewed
interest rate fears and uncertainty about what fall-out there would be from
Orange County, California, filing for municipal bankruptcy.
South Africa's first international bond offering since the end of apartheid,
a Dollars 500m (Pounds 304.8m) issue, was over-subscribed. The issue was
increased to Dollars 750m.
</TEXT>
