<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): I'm suing my solicitors
 -Briefcase Q&amp;A
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
I intended to sell my house in 1987 but the deal fell through because of a
defect in my title to the property. I am now pursuing the solicitors
involved for damages, including interest charges on the money I would have
had if the sale had proceeded. Are such charges assessable for income
purposes?
Broadly speaking, interest on damages is taxable as interest but any
interest element in the calculation of damages is not. The damages
themselves are liable to capital gains tax, of course, but you probably
would escape by virtue of extra-statutory concession D33 (capital gains tax
on compensation and damages). You can get the free booklet of concessions,
IR1, from your tax office.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
