<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 94 / Letters to the Editor: In train for better value today than
in railways' golden age
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr CS GUEST
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I am no defender of British Rail but I recently came across a copy of
Punch, dated May 19 1937, in which the LMS Railway made the proud boast that
the cost of its third-class travel was one old penny (0.4166 new pence) a
mile. l decided to put this to the test against the Pounds 19.50 I recently
paid for a day return from Bristol to Torquay (196 miles there and back).
In 1937 this journey would have cost me 16 shillings and 4 pence (8l. 66p).
On this basis, the journey price has gone up by a factor of 23.88.
Taking an average take-home wage of Pounds 3 a week in 1937 and of Pounds
150 today, wages have gone up by a factor of 50. If anyone can prove
otherwise, I will withdraw my assertion that rail travel today represents
better value than it did in 1937.
CS Guest,
30 Longmead Avenue,
Horfield,
Bristol BS7 8QD
</TEXT>
