<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Investing for Income): The new rules test
skill of managers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The new rules for personal equity plans are keeping fund managers busy as
they try to work out the best ways to take advantage of them.
Andy Harrison, chief executive of Clerical Medical unit trusts - which
postponed launching a new Extra Income trust, investing in fixed interest
and equities in equal measures - says he can see a Pep with 45 per cent
invested in gilts, 15 per cent in convertibles, and 40 per cent split
between debentures and preference shares.
Although a direct holding of gilts does not qualify for the full Pounds
6,000 annual general plan allowance, a unit trust which holds at least 50
per cent of its assets in eligible Pep investments does qualify.
Harrison is cautious about using convertibles (shares or bonds which pay a
fixed rate of interest and give the holder the right to convert them into
the company's ordinary shares).
This is because their link to the underlying share value makes them more
volatile than preference shares or bonds. But Justin Urquhart-Stewart, a
director at Barclays Stockbrokers, believes in convertibles as a way of
offering protection against inflation.
He says, however: 'These are the golden rules. Never buy a convertible of a
company in which you would not want to be an ordinary shareholder.
'Make sure the income from the convertible is higher than the yield on the
ordinary shares, and that the conversion premium is not so high that future
conversion into the ordinary shares is unlikely.'
He adds: 'If someone wanted high income with safety, I would suggest 40 per
cent in bonds and preference shares, 40 per cent in convertibles, 10 per
cent in cash, and 10 per cent in overseas (European or US) equities.'
</TEXT>
