<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Companies): NFC's glamour fades - Simon
Davies analyses its sagging fortunes and what needs to be done / Company in
the news
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NFC's 1993-1994 profit figure, announced on Tuesday to market gloom, was a
sour finale to a year that has seen the former glamour stock dragged down
from grace with an almighty thud.
Once the leading participant in the high-growth logistics and distribution
sector, it rode the recession with extreme ease and steady profits. But the
slide in the economy finally caught up with the former government-owned
National Freight Consortium.
Throw in the shock departure of its chief executive, plus the first-ever
suspension of profit-sharing to employees in a company renowned for its
paternalism, and the result has been a free-falling share price.
Each of the past three sets of quarterly results has been met with a share
price decline of at least 7 per cent. In late trading on Friday, NFC's
shares stood at 145p, representing a hefty decline from the start of the
year when they stood at 234p.
NFC has two major businesses. It owns Allied Pickfords and has a substantial
house-moving operation. This, inevitably, was a casualty of weak property
markets in the UK and the US, and its recovery has been slow.
NFC's fortunes were, however, supported by its transport and logistics
business. (Logistics is the jargon term for the new breed of former haulage
and transport companies).
Once, retailers tied up their own money in expensive stocks. No longer. In
the mid-1980s, logistics companies installed complex computer systems,
expanded their warehouse space and emerged as one-stop shops for the
efficient storage and distribution of goods. Retailers pushed the burden of
controlling stocks on to the middle-man. Typical customers are retailers
such as Sainsbury and Marks and Spencer.
This new and exciting concept was extraordinarily profitable in the
mid-1980s and had the added attraction of contracts of up to five years in
length. Companies such as Exel, Hays, Tibbett &amp; Britten, Christian Salvesen
and Transport Development Group all made merry. But, when the recession
came, clients had to continue paying the same rates under long-term
contracts.
It was different when the contracts came up for renewal. Because of
increased competition among logistics companies, and retailers' ability to
resume their own distribution, reduced rates were quickly on offer.
NFC looked at two routes to avoid this this path. First, it moved to
persuade other industries, from oil companies to manufacturers, to pass on
their distribution activities at better rates than retailers would pay. This
proved reasonably successful.
Second, NFC moved into Europe and the US, both comparatively undeveloped
markets, offering attractive business opportunities. But market development
overseas has been slow, and acquisitions have proven difficult.
Indeed, acquisitions worth Pounds 10m in Germany contributed an unexpected
level of loss last year.
Against this more difficult background, Peter Sherlock stepped unto the
breach early in 1993. He came up with a Pounds 45m strategic plan, focusing
NFC on distribution and moving services and attacking its cost base. The
ideas won support, but patience became stretched at the absence of results
and he left suddenly in August.
NFC intends to continue the programme, at an increased cost of Pounds 50m,
but is now looking to accelerate the cost-cutting process. Profits' growth
will be slow, however: UBS Securities, the house broker, forecasts a pre-tax
figure this year of Pounds 115m.
NFC now needs to bring in a credible new chief executive and re-focus
attention on its skills as the leader in the increasingly sophisticated UK
logistics market. It could, however, take some time to win back its faded
glamour.
</TEXT>
<XX>
