<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 94 / Rao party faces state poll defeat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
India's governing Congress (I) party is facing serious defeat in the latest
round of state elections, according to results announced yesterday.
As vote-counting continued in Andhra Pradesh, home state of Mr Narasimha
Rao, the prime minister, Congress faced its most humiliating and politically
significant defeat at the hands of the regional Telugu Desam party.
In Karnataka, the centrist Janata Dal was emerging as a clear winner, and
Congress was also trailing in the border state of Sikkim.
'Our performance is simply shattering,' said Mr Pranab Mukherjee, commerce
minister, on television.
In the western state of Goa, the party was faring better, running neck and
neck with an alliance led by the Hindu nationalist Bhartiya Janata party.
The outcome could herald a disruptive bout of squabbling among party chiefs
but is not expected to threaten the stability of Mr Rao's government.
</TEXT>
