<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Companies): Buy-backs boost the recs - The
week ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MONDAY/TUESDAY
WEDNESDAY/THURSDAY: Dividends will be on everyone's minds when seven of the
12 regional electricity companies (recs) report. Analysts are expecting
average growth of about 20 per cent.
One reason for such healthy increases is that most of them have been busily
buying back their shares over the past year. By spreading the same amount of
cash over fewer shares, they have found a reasonably economical way of
enhancing shareholder returns.
A few companies such as Eastern (Monday) and Southern (Tuesday) have not
been as active in share buy-backs, so their dividend increases will be of
special interest. Forecasts are for pre-tax profits of about Pounds 85m for
Eastern and Pounds 92m for Southern, and dividend increases of almost 20 per
cent. Eastern's propensity for surprises has some market observers hoping
for news of a special pay-out.
Yorkshire (Thursday), which is forecast to report profits of about Pounds
98m, is also a promising candidate for special payments. The failed bid for
a Swedish energy group has left it with a cash pile of about Pounds 100m,
which it had not expected to have. Needless to say, investors are hoping for
an early Christmas present.
Northern Electricity (Monday) is expected to show one of the larger dividend
increases with a rise of about 22 per cent. The market is anticipating
pre-tax profits of about Pounds 61m. South Western (Thursday) and London
(Wednesday) are likely to trail behind with dividend increases of about 18
per cent. Forecasts are for interim profits of Pounds 46m at South Western
and Pounds 85m at London.
Some investors are hoping for a little clarification from Manweb
(Wednesday), which is expected to report profits of about Pounds 53m.
Questions are likely to be asked on the abrupt departure of its finance
director earlier this year.
TUESDAY: Greenalls Group is expected to report pre-tax profits for the year
to September of about Pounds 76m (after Pounds 9m of reorganisation costs),
against Pounds 68m a year earlier. The diverse group with pub, off-licence,
hotel and drinks distribution interests will be boosted by the first
full-year contribution from the Devenish pub estate.
WEDNESDAY: Southern Water is expected to report interims of about Pounds
68.5m, a 6 per cent increase on last year. The dividend could rise by almost
10 per cent to 8.45p. Southern is one of the few water companies to enjoy
earnings enhancement from its non-regulated businesses. This is likely to
show further improvement.
WEDNESDAY: Chubb Security, the electronic alarms and locks group, is
forecast to report pre-tax profits of Pounds 38m-Pounds 41m (Pounds 34.2m)
for its first six months.
WEDNESDAY: Half-year results from British Land could be overshadowed by
events at Stanhope, the troubled developer from which it is hoping to
acquire a half share in the City of London's Broadgate office complex. If
Stanhope goes into receivership when its banking facilities run out next
Monday, British Land will lose its 29.9 per cent stake in the developer.
Analysts are expecting the interim figures to show profits before tax of
about Pounds 20m, against Pounds 13.1m last year. THURSDAY: The City will
pay close attention to the core engineering activities of Trafalgar House,
the UK-based group with interests ranging from property and construction to
ocean liners. Analysts forecast full-year profits of between Pounds 50m and
Pounds 55m, after a Pounds 16m restructuring charge, against losses last
time of Pounds 347.2m after Pounds 397m exceptional costs.
</TEXT>
