<DATELINE>
   MAPUTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Joaquim Chissano, Mozambique's president since 1986, was sworn in for a
new five-year term yesterday with a pledge that peace would last in the
war-weary southern African country. 'This spectre of war has been removed.
Peace has come to stay,' he told a crowd of thousands in Maputo's
Independence Square, among them his former civil war rival Mr Afonso
Dhlakama, leader of the main opposition Renamo party.
Mr Chissano also made a plea for reconciliation. 'This is a time for us to
continue healing all our wounds and overcome distrust. We must know how to
begin a new relationship, without preconceptions and without rancour. We
must bury forever our hatreds and renounce vindictiveness once and for all,'
he said. 'Let us forgive the wrongs of the past.'
