<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Bosnia clouds EU summit hopes on eastern Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, ESSEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EU leaders open a two-day summit in Essen, Germany, today to discuss future
integration of eastern Europe, an issue clouded by the Bosnian crisis.
The summit is also affected by Spanish threats to block the entry of
Austria, Sweden and Finland into the Union next year unless Madrid receives,
improved fishing rights.
These 'hostage-taking' tactics were denounced this week by Mr Jacques
Delors, outgoing president of the European Commission and possible contender
for the presidency of France. With host Chancellor Helmut Kohl, he is
expected to be central to the summit.
At a meeting of the European socialists in Essen yesterday, Mr Delors said
he would try to convince EU leaders to consider new ways to combat
unemployment. But the 'intellectual laziness and traditionalist ideas of
some' would make it difficult, he said.
The focus of the Essen summit is a German paper on the integration of six
former communist countries - Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Slovakia,
Bulgaria and Romania - into the European Union.
Leaders of the six will tomorrow be offered further modest trade
liberalisation, broader political contact, and promised guidelines, next
spring, for adapting their economies and legal codes to the single European
market. However, the package avoids a commitment to reform the common
agricultural policy and regional aid funds, without which the cost of
admitting the east Europeans would be prohibitive. 'This is one of the big
weaknesses in the document,' said a senior EU official.
This reflects intra-EU tensions over the German-led desire to secure stable
borders to its east. A Franco-German compromise committing minimum sums of
Dollars 6.7bn over the next five years to the east Europeans, and Dollars
3.27bn to North Africa and the Middle East, is likely to be agreed. Despite
Chancellor Kohl's consensus-building skills, senior diplomats predict
difficult discussions over Bosnia. The UK and France have contributed the
bulk of European forces in the UN peace-keeping effort, and are nervous
about possible German support for lifting the UN arms embargo against the
Bosnian Moslem government.
They believe that this would force a humiliating withdrawal of UN troops,
fuelling tensions within Nato and with Russia, which has become bolder in
its support for the Serbian government headed by President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
