<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / UK Property Review (12): The wind has been stirring again -
Manchester and the North-West / Probably the best that can be said about the
north-west is that things are no longer static and trends are certainly not
going down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As Graeme Wood, a partner in the Manchester office of property consultants
King Sturge, puts it: 'The economic pendulum never swings as wildly in the
north-west as it does in the south-east.'
Nothing bubbled in north-west England in the late 1980s so nothing burst in
the recession. Even the largest concentration of newly-built offices - in
Manchester's former docklands at Salford Quays and Trafford Park - left a
relatively minor but manageable oversupply problem when compared with
London.
The north-west found itself not so much in a deepening trough as in the
doldrums. This year, the wind has been stirring again as the regional
economy has picked up. Indeed, as DTZ Debenham Thorpe's Manchester office
points out, the region's gross domestic product grew by 2.7 per cent last
year compared with the UK's 2 per cent - a faster pick-up than any other UK
region. Demand in property markets, which always lags, was bound to show
itself this year.
Although there is an underlying pent-up demand, however, take-up is patchy.
Partly this is because industry and commerce is still unsure about recovery,
limiting companies' confidence to move, but it is also the result of a
shortage of good, modern space to move into.
North-west England has a surfeit of old space in commercial, retail, and
industrial markets, much of it unlettable.
Alan Murch, managing director of Richard Ellis's regional practice, says
205,000 sq ft of office space came on the market in central Manchester in
the first half of this year and take-ups or purchases totalled 157,000 sq
ft.
But this is in a local market that started 1994 with 1.3m sq ft of office
space available. The figures suggest a reasonably quick take-up of good,
air-conditioned space, but a continuing struggle to let a large rump of old
offices.
So, while there is optimism that the shortage of good space will drive a
steady trickle of new developments, what to do about the old space is going
to remain a problem, particularly when incentives to persuade businesses to
relocate were tied to temporary subsidies of rentals in their old premises
while they were being marketed.
Office rentals betray the underlying reality. Although the top headline rent
for the region - in Manchester's professional services core - has been at
Pounds 21 a sq ft for a couple of years, DTZ Debenham Thorpe's research
paints a gloomier picture.
Its 1994 review puts the figure at Pounds 14.50 in 1990, rising through
Pounds 20.50 in 1991 to Pounds 21.50 in 1992, but falling back through
Pounds 18.50 to Pounds 17.50 this year.
In Salford Quays - outside the Manchester core but only 10 minutes away -
the net rate being paid for modern space with air-conditioning is less than
Pounds 8, once incentives and special deals have been stripped out. People
contemplating a move within the Manchester core, but not in such a hurry
they cannot force prices down, say they do not expect to pay more than
Pounds 16 net in the next year.
Salford Quays' prices are proving attractive, especially since Manchester
Ship Canal, now a subsidiary of Peel Holdings and one of the main
developers, decided to break down some of its unlet properties into 50,000
sq ft or smaller packets, instead of waiting for big, single users wanting
120,000 sq ft at a time.
British Nuclear Fuels is taking 50,000 sq ft, relocating some functions from
Warrington and Preston. Halliwell Landau, an expanding Manchester law firm,
has moved some functions out of the Manchester core to 'the Quays'.
Robert Hough, ship canal chairman, says Quay West, the company's flagship
office block, is now 90 per cent let. Of other developments in the old
docklands, there appears now to be about 600,000 sq ft still unlet, but this
compares with 1.5m sq ft less than 18 months ago.
Mr Hough, however, points to an uncomfortable truth. Although low interest
rates should encourage development, higher net rents will be needed to
improve yields enough for anyone to do it. This in turn will require much
more confidence generally throughout industry and commerce to persuade more
people to move and so drive demand.
With DTZ Debenham Thorpe estimating best office rents in Chester and
Warrington at about Pounds 11.50 and at Pounds 11.00 in Liverpool, there
does not appear much basis for optimism until the economy is much stronger.
The industrial scene is even less encouraging. Roger Shufflebottom of
Manchester's The Elliott Partnership says: 'Yields have dropped to
unprecedented levels over the last nine months, with less than 7 per cent
quoted in one case.'
He says that after little activity in 1991 and 1992, there has been a slow
increase in design-and-build industrial and warehousing projects for
specific end-users. There has been hardly any speculative development - and
then only in traditionally 'safe' areas near motorway junctions, such as
Warrington and Trafford Park.
But even these sites proved not as attractive as developers hoped, Mr
Shufflebottom says, although - according to DTZ Debenham Thorpe -
Warrington's average industrial rents have this year climbed back to their
1990 level of Pounds 4 a sq ft. Chester at Pounds 3, Liverpool at Pounds
3.30, Preston at Pounds 3.60 and Manchester at Pounds 3.85 have yet to
recover the pre-recession levels.
Probably the best that can be said about the north-west is that things are
no longer static and trends are certainly not going down. But for the market
to be healthy, there are still too many bargains about for industrial and
commercial tenants who can afford them, and too little certainty of good
long-term profits for developers to chance their arms.
</TEXT>
<XX>
