<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / UK Property Review (11): Yorkshire caution curbs speculation
 -Leeds and the North-East / If there is no substantial speculative office
building in the city soon, Leeds will lose the edge it has established over
Birmingham and Manchester
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MALCOLM PITHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The feel-good factor may still be an elusive one for many companies, but not
so in Leeds. Of all northern cities, Leeds, with about 700,000 residents,
has established itself as a pre-eminent financial and services centre.
Southern-based corporates, along with government departments dispersing into
the regions have been persuaded to move to the city and prosperity seems to
abound. The latest arrival is Direct Line which, much to the astonishment of
local residents, says it chose Leeds because of the 'neutral Leeds accent,'
vital for their telephone operation. The company has taken over 90,000 sq ft
of office space in Headrow House for its direct insurance selling.
There is no doubt Leeds has a dynamic service sector. Last year, more than
300,000 sq ft of office space was either let or sold. The city has
diversified its industrial economy over the years and is now reaping the
reward.
The office market in Leeds has largely remained on track during the
recession and the city's links with specialist, financial and legal services
has actually expanded during the past 12 months. There are also sites ready
for speculative development or pre-commitment from tenants, including the
remainder of the impressive Granary Wharf scheme. This riverside plan is
proving to be a catalyst for the development of a previously untapped area,
south of the city but within walking distance for staff who want to amble
into the city at lunchtime.
When Leeds Development Corporation was set up in 1988, most of the
waterfront area was derelict. Now, all that has changed and the LDC has
invested some Pounds 600,000 in a new footbridge linking the city with the
scheme. This in turn has led to even further development, including a Pounds
6m brewery wharf museum by Tetley's. In all, some Pounds 72m of the Pounds
255m private sector investment has been attracted to the waterfront.
Despite all the encouraging signs in and around the city however, the
Yorkshire caution which perhaps helped it through the deepest parts of the
recession, is still holding everything in check. Potential development plans
are in place but if there is no substantial speculative office building in
the city soon, Leeds will lose the edge it has established over Birmingham
and Manchester. There are rumours that at least one of three leading
developers will be moving into the city early next year.
There has also recently been an upsurge in out-of-town development, led
initially by the growth of retail developments away from the city centre.
Companies are now taking office space adjacent to motorways where rents are,
at least for the moment, significantly cheaper and where staff and customers
have little or no car parking problems.
Business people in Leeds say, with a fair degree of pride, that it is
caution which helped many local firms survive and in some cases prosper,
during the recession and it will not easily cast aside.
Mike Hartley, a senior director with Richard Ellis Regional, based in Leeds,
says: 'The lack of speculative development in the city is surprising when
one considers that Leeds has not suffered a reduction in its rental levels
over the past few years. There is no doubt that rentals are now rising and
Leeds is certainly perceived as a place where funds are available to
invest.'
The city has enjoyed a good rental progression with figures showing a 9.1
per cent increase between 1979 and 1994. Top office rental values in Leeds
now stand at about Pounds 17-Pounds 18 a sq ft which reflects the shortage
of prime accommodation. The rents are more in line with Birmingham and
Manchester although the lack of new development has inevitably reduced the
number of investment transactions which have taken place.
The largest transaction recorded during the first half of the year was the
purchase of 21-22 Park Place by Pearl Assurance for a reported Pounds 5.5m.
Eagle Star, however, recently completed a deal for 50,000 sq ft of office
space, effectively taking the last available prime office building in Leeds.
Mr Hartley says: 'There has been a lack of confidence but the recession did
not bite as deeply in Leeds as elsewhere. Here, everything is in place and
the rents are slowly coming up and there are major development opportunities
with planning permission. 'There is no doubt people are confident and they
have good reason to be here, but they are also extremely cautious. So it is
only a matter of time before speculative schemes do go ahead. That will make
all the difference.'
The upturn in the regional property market is undoubtedly being driven by
the financial and business services sector and this is why Leeds is well
placed.
According to Alistair Russell, a senior partner at Jones Lang Wootton, which
has recently opened new offices in Carlton Tower in Leeds, business
confidence in the area is very high. The demand for office accommodation is,
he says, positive and improving. 'There is a very positive mood about, even
if it is tempered slightly with the traditional caution of the area. We have
expanded here for a very good reason and feel that companies are on the
verge of a significant change for the better.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
