<PROFILE>_AN-ELIDCAHCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941209
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / UK Property Review (9): Popular option for many occupiers -
Business Parks / Whatever the outcome of the town-centre versus out-of-town
argument, we could soon see rising headline rents for the best office space
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANNE STEADMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is taking a tough stance on transport and the environment.
And the debate on the relative merits of city centre versus out-of-town
offices looks set to reopen.
After PPG6 - the planning policy statement regarding out-of-town shopping
development, which appears to have been unswervingly enforced in the light
of recent decisions despite howls of protest from the superstore operators -
it seems that PPG13, aimed at preventing further development in the green
belt, is going to become equally significant to the future growth of
business parks.
The decision by Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, to throw out Lloyd's
Register of Shipping's proposals to build a 350,000 sq ft headquarters at
Bramshott Place at Liphook, Hampshire is being cited as a landmark case.
Lloyd's chose the 50-acre site which already had planning for 100,000 sq ft
 -essentially to replace the previous hospital on part of the land - after
an extensive search which involved considering some 70 other locations
across south-east England.
The register's plans were fully supported by the local planning authorities
and the local community which is set to suffer job losses as a result of
Ministry of Defence closures.
The fact that the amount of buildings proposed by Lloyd's far exceeded the
existing permission was only one element in the secretary of state's reasons
for turning down the application.
With little public transport available locally, the new headquarters would
clearly be heavily orientated towards car-users - with both staff and
visitors driving relatively long distances to reach it.
Despite all the time and effort - not to mention hard cash - that a
disappointed Lloyd's has invested in Bramshott Place, it will not appeal.
Danish developer Danbuild, the owner of the site, is now considering various
options, says its joint agent Roger Saper of surveyor Jones Lang Wootton.
John Batsford of surveyor Chesterton considers that from now on business
park developers and funding institutions will look very carefully not only
at public transport connections to prospective sites but also to the
provision of additional on-site facilities (such as shops and restaurants)
for staff.
But while the longer-term trend - reinforced by government policy - may be
back to the town centre, business park space remains a popular option - with
a whole range of occupiers including banks, insurance companies, accountants
and public sector agencies, all of whom employ significant numbers of
clerical staff which it was traditionally considered were more attracted to
jobs in town centres.
The rate of business park development has slowed during the downturn over
the past couple of years, in line with other commercial property sectors.
Paul Ives at surveyor Erdman Lewis estimates that from a peak of 15m sq ft
of business park space completed in 1990 the volume dropped to less than 2m
sq ft in 1993. Today, construction is unlikely to begin without a pre-let in
place.
Arlington - with some 7.2m sq ft already developed, 8.5m sq ft with planning
and a further 12. 9m sq ft at application stage - is the largest specialist
developer of business parks in the UK. It is one of the few which have
continued to build speculative space over the past year or so.
At the Oxford Business Park - the old Cowley works - Arlington has just
completed an office village of 32,000 sq ft in five units. Already, says
agent Ian Warboys of surveyor Strutt &amp; Parker, solicitors have been
instructed to proceed with letting documentation on behalf of two potential
tenants.
And At Hatfield Business Park, Arlington has just finished two warehouse
buildings totalling 95,000 sq ft.
The Hatfield Park epitomises the evolution of Arlington's philosophy which
has moved from a mixed to an all-office environment and is now shifting back
to a mixed-use park. However, Warboys emphasises that careful planning is
necessary to house both office and industrial users on the same site.
For example, large lorries need specially designed roads, parking and yards.
On the other hand, no image-aware director of, say, a professional business
wants to entertain clients looking out of his windows at warehouses and
heavy vehicles. So different uses at all Arlington's new parks are sited in
separate zones.
Stockley Park at Heathrow, arguably the UK's first true business park, is
still regarded as the flagship. But although there is planning for a further
600,000 sq ft, there is presently no new space available. And it seems that
demand is predominantly for new space. The second-hand buildings at Stockley
are failing to achieve premium rents says Richard Storey of surveyor Richard
Ellis. Top rents at the height of the boom reached as much as Pounds 32 a sq
ft. Rent obtained in the last major letting - to Reebok earlier this year -
was Pounds 26 a sq ft. However, second-hand space on offer is going for
less.
Against this, Arlington reports that rents for second-hand space at its
parks are holding up well - particularly at the successful Birmingham
Business Park. And as for new space, Arlington's pre-let to KPMG Peat
Marwick at Reading Business Park achieved Pounds 23-Pounds 24 a sq ft -
which compares with about Pounds 18.50 a sq ft for high-quality offices in
Reading town centre. In general, headline rents at good business parks
appear to remain static. But there is evidence that landlords are taking a
harder line on short-term break clauses in leases. And rent-free periods are
becoming shorter. Whatever the eventual outcome of the growing
in-town/out-of-town argument - and this one will run and run - we could soon
see rising headline rents for the best office space; wherever it is.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6552 Subdividers and Developers, Ex Cemeteries.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
