<DOCNO>FT944-4069</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-ELIDCAHBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941209
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / UK Property Review (8): Improvement is patchy and slow -
Industrial Properties / Most regions report steady increases in both sales
and lettings and also 'general confidence'. But industrial rents are still
falling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANNE STEADMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Reflecting the economy in general, the industrial property market has shown
signs of increased activity this year. However, again as with the economy,
improvement is patchy and slow.
Reports from most regions indicate steady increases in both sales and
lettings and also 'general confidence'. But industrial rents are still
falling. Figures from surveyor Richard Ellis show a monthly decline of 0.4
per cent for October. And capital values have again been knocked back as a
result of the softening investment yields which have affected all property
sectors.
In the south-east, where heavy industry has been declining for the past 15
years, this year has seen greater activity among light industrial companies.
A key feature has been the mopping up of the considerable amount of
second-hand space. Now, in some locations - for example Guildford and
several towns round the M25 - most of this space has been taken up, leaving
only limited choice.
Richard Storey of surveyor Richard Ellis notes that second-hand space has
let well for several reasons. Firstly, occupiers have been able to negotiate
better deals with hard-pressed landlords. In addition, while confidence
remains fragile, industrialists tentatively expanding have been able to
secure shorter, flexible leases, minimising longer-term commitments.
Even where confidence is stronger, companies have often preferred to take
cheaper, second-hand space for 'image' reasons.
Surveyor Healey &amp; Baker confirms the trend to shorter leases. In an analysis
of industrial transactions completed by the firm over the past three months
it found that 43 per cent had been struck on the basis of 10-year terms and
35 per cent on five-year terms. This compares with 11 per cent each for the
more conventional 'institutional' 15- and 25-year leases. As a caveat,
however, Healey &amp; Baker says that landlords are still likely to resist
shorter leases for tenants with poor covenants.
Institutional investors began 1994 in a welter of enthusiasm for industrial
property in view of its comparatively attractive yields compared with those
of gilts - yields on high coupon 15-year gilts had fallen to close to 6.5
per cent - bonds and office and retail property. In a hurry to increase
their holdings, and with few good standing investments on the market, some
decided to create their own through development. Several projects were
undertaken in selected locations on a speculative basis by parties including
Axa Equity &amp; Law, AMP Asset management, Hill Samuel and BZW.
Now, however, with long-term gilts closer to 9 per cent following the
increase in interest rates, industrial property looks less appealing. Most
of the institutions have lost their appetite for speculative funding and
gone away. But not all of them. James Thornton of surveyor Jones Lang
Wootton cites a recent transaction in West Bromwich where a pension fund
client is putting up the cash for a speculative 152,000 sq ft industrial
project by a local developer. Terms reflect a yield of 8.25 per cent on a
rent of Pounds 4 a sq ft with rental cover for three years.
Almost in isolation, one segment of the industrial market flourished
throughout the recession - high bay warehouses: buildings which defined
roughly have a minimum floor area of 100,000 sq ft, eaves height of 30
ft-plus and site cover of 45 per cent or less.
The growth of the development of this type of building is a result of the
revolution in distribution led by, but not confined to, the food retailing
sector. The use of bar-coding and its allied computer-driven stock control
has meant that retailers have been able to switch from supply-led to
demand-led distribution systems - meaning larger warehouses, less storage
and more selling space at retail outlets.
These new methods have enabled retailers to cut costs dramatically. Guy
Frampton of surveyor Hillier Parker estimates that food retailers have
halved their distribution costs to 6 per cent of turnover over the past five
years by operating from these specialist buildings.
Location is another important side to the distribution equation. Development
began in the 'Midlands Triangle' - the area within 30 minutes' lorry drive
of the M1-M6 junction. The most high-profile pioneer was the Gaseley-Church
Commissioners Magna Park in Lutterworth. Now Warrington and Wakefield are
also popular with, according to Hillier Parker, some 11 per cent of the high
bay warehouse stock (by floor space).
Investment yields at Magna Park in April were as low as 5.75 per cent. They
have now eased back and the latest transaction at the park is going through
at around 6.5 per cent.
Clear support for predictions that we shall see rising rents and a new burst
of industrial development in 1995 comes with evidence of rising land prices.
From a peak of Pounds 1m an acre at the height of the boom, prices in the
prime area west of London fell to a low of Pounds 400,000 an acre. Now,
according to Richard Ellis's Storey, deals have been done at Pounds 600,000
 -and there are others in the pipeline in excess of that figure.
Healey &amp; Baker's John Organ puts Heathrow prices even higher at Pounds
750,000 an acre. And, looking at the regions, Organ's current figures for
industrial land in Bristol, Birmingham, Manchester, Newcastle and Leeds are
Pounds 350,000, Pounds 200,000, Pounds 170,000, Pounds 70,000 and Pounds
175,000 an acre respectively - all above the bottom-of-the-market prices in
1992. Owner-occupiers are coming back into the market, adds Organ,
particularly where developers are prepared to sell land and not look for
extra profit from design-and-build work.
It could soon also become feasible to develop inner city traditional
industrial areas again. London's Park Royal, for instance, has been given
Assisted Area status and with improvements to the North Circular Road Park
Royal could feature on developers' and funds' shopping lists again - 'sooner
rather than later' says Storey.
Organ, however, reckons that the government should do more. Most occupiers
operating on the UK's traditional estates, he argues, are small businesses
which depend on supplying and servicing the few larger occupiers and the
wider local business community.
When these larger occupiers move out to more efficient premises on
'green-field' sites with better environments and infrastructure, many of the
remaining small business find it difficult to survive. Not only are jobs
lost but there is the likelihood that the former larger factory site will be
sold to a retail park developer.
In order to regenerate our inner city industrial areas, Organ suggests, the
government should offer 100 per cent building allowances. Such an incentive
would encourage developers, funds and present occupiers to redevelop to
modern acceptable standards. Inner city economies and communities still need
local industry, maintains Organ.
</TEXT>
