<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / UK Property Review (5): Litigation is still clogging up
courts - The Valuation Controversy / It is no surprise that the profession
has spent the past two years engaged in critical self-examination
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The reputation of valuers suffered more in the recession than any other
profession. Litigation surrounding negligent valuations is still clogging up
the courts. The widely differing valuations of Queens Moat Houses hotel
portfolio undermined the credibility of traditional open market valuations.
It is, therefore, no surprise that the profession has spent the last two
years engaged in critical self-examination. Since most of the outstanding
litigation is between valuers and banks, valuations made for secured lending
purposes were the first to be overhauled.
In conjunction with the British Bankers Association, the Royal Institution
of Chartered Surveyors issued a guidance note giving detailed advice on how
valuations conducted for banks should be carried out.
This introduced the concept of 'estimated realisation price' (ERP) - the
price that would be achieved if the property was put on the market
immediately, rather than the price that would be achieved if a sale was
agreed today.
The wider response to the painful experience of recession came with the
Mallinson Report, which was published in April and contains 43 detailed
recommendations.
The main message was that the existing rules and techniques for valuation
are broadly satisfactory, but need to be refined.
The institution acted rapidly on one of the report's main recommendations:
that guidance for valuers contained in the Red and White Books should be
consolidated in a single volume and supplemented with additional rules.
The old Red Book was actually very limited in scope, laying down rules for
valuations which would be relied upon by third parties other than the
client. In practice, this covers valuations likely to appear in public
documents such as company accounts and prospectuses.
The new Red Book will be much wider in scope, covering virtually all
valuations apart from advice given to potential sellers in the course of
agency work.
It also introduces the concept of estimated realisation price as an
established basis of valuation. The institution hopes that the contrast
between estimated realisation price and open market valuation will increase
understanding among clients.
Not everyone agrees. Some in the profession think that enshrining an
alternative valuation basis will cause confusion.
How clients react to ERP remains to be seen. But the new Red Book goes to
great lengths to improve mutual understanding between the valuer and the
client.
This was another of the messages from the Mallinson Report. It said, for
example, that valuers should decline instructions where the client was not
prepared to disclose the purpose of the valuation.
The new Red Book also demands that valuers obtain written instructions
before undertaking work. Insurance companies have estimated that 45 per cent
of professional indemnity claims could be avoided avoided if the
instructions to the valuer from the client had been written down.
But the new Red Book is not a definitive response to the Mallinson report.
The report recommended that the 'all-risk yield' method used by valuers
should be refined, and that alternative techniques should be explored to
provide a cross-check for results. The institution has set up working
parties to look at these issues. Some would like to go further, faster. The
British Association of Hotel Accountants has suggested a method of valuing
hotels based on discounted cash flow analysis rather than market evidence
and yields.
This has been rejected by the institution on the grounds that the worth of a
property to its owner - as defined by discounted cash flow techniques - may
have little connection to its value in the open market.
Besides, present accounting rules demand that published accounts should show
open market valuations based on best practice as defined by the Red Book.
However, the lesson of recession is that valuers can not afford simply to
state open market value without explanation if their valuation diverges from
underlying considerations of worth.
Over time, valuers will have to accept the Mallinson Report's insistence
that valuers should be familiar with a range of approaches to valuation and
be prepared to explain their findings to clients.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
