<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / UK Property Review (4): Popularity soared in past two years
 -Tenders and Auctions / An analysis by JLW reveals that more properties are
being put out for bids
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LAWSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Discussion on the merits of differing religions occupies little time in the
life of the average property professional. They are more likely to be deep
in debate about the advantages of buying shops rather than offices.
The buying and selling of such investments, however, often appears to have
all the hallmarkings of a doctrinal division.
Auctions have soared in popularity over the past couple of years, bringing
an air of nervousness to advisers who have never set foot in a sale room.
Public exhibitions of bidding frenzy bring a shiver of discomfort to those
used to playing off unidentified buyers and sellers in quiet offices or on
mobile phones.
But they now face questions from clients about whether auctions are better
than tender or private treaty. Such debates are futile, says Richard
Auterac, auctions specialist for Jones Lang Wootton. 'It is a bit like
comparing religions. None is better than any other.' There is no hard and
objective evidence to make a meaningful comparison.
A sector analysis launched by JLW has certainly helped show that business is
increasing. The Auction Results Analysis System (Aras) brought together
figures for the first time from six top London auctioneers. But such changes
are too often attributed to the method of sale, when they might reflect
general changes in the market, says Mr Auterac.
Explosion of turnover last year and a fall-off in the past six months, for
example, have been matched in the private treaty market. This is not
surprising, as Mr Auterac believes auctions give a more accurate picture of
the property market than the big, glossy deals which attract headlines. They
reflect the tone of the wider market, which involves thousands of private
property companies and individual investors.
Proselytisers insist that selling under the hammer does have advantages
which outlast general market movements, however. 'It provides a quick and
efficient method of sale, avoiding the procrastination often associated with
private treaty,' says Patrick Kerr of Allsop &amp; Co, the largest UK operator
with sales of more than Pounds 200m in the past 12 months.
Auctions can also squeeze out extra value from bidders spurred by the fact
that they can plainly see the 'whites of the competitor's eyes'.
Certain kinds of property are well suited to such open and dramatic
techniques. Unique buildings need an open forum to determine market value,
says Cliff Krieger of Chesterton. Investment property can be hard to price
any other way when demand soars above supply, while banks, receivers and
trustees also need a public stage to show they are fulfilling a duty to
obtain maximum returns. The market has been flooded with this kind of
property over the past two years. Banks, for example, are now willing to
unload vast property holdings at knock-down prices, says veteran auctioneer
Simon Rigall of Conrad Ritblat Sinclair Goldsmith.
Local authorities rushed in during a period of grace when the government
allowed them to keep capital receipts. Conrad Ritblat sold 300 council
properties in this blue patch up to early 1994. Brewers have shed pubs under
orders from the Monopolies Commission while retailers and banks raised cash
through sale and leaseback deals.
The surge appears to be abating, however. The number of lots fell by almost
40 per cent and sales by 50 per cent in the three months to September,
according to Aras. This reflects the end of council property dumping but
also demonstrates Mr Auterac's case that auctions follow the general market,
which is now more uncertain over rental growth and interest rate movements.
John Townsend of Erdman Lewis says yields are suffering because of wider
interest rate moves, but volume should remain stable if sellers are not
over-ambitious. Richard Ellis is so confident of institutional interest in
selling assets this way that the firm is joining the market by setting up a
partnership with Dublin-based auctioneer Gunne.
It may be a tough business to enter. Shortage of quality property could turn
the market into a test of survival of the fittest, says Mr Krieger. Over the
long-term, however, most professionals believe the sector will continue to
grow as bigger dealers taste the advantages of auction selling. And if some
form of objective analysis can be devised to illustrate this difference, it
will expand even more, adds Mr Auterac.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
