<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / London Stock Exchange: BSkyB debut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and JEFFREY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Initial dealing in BSkyB shares saw turnover of some 45m in the last two
hours of trading in London. The stock, which was only priced yesterday
morning, opened at an 11p premium to its 256p striking price and held steady
to end the day at 268 1/2 p.
The shares began trading simultaneously in London and New York. They will
enter the UK Stock Exchange's official list next Thursday and BSkyB is
expected to be an early candidate for the FT-SE 100 Index. The offer price
translates to a capitalisation of Pounds 4.4bn, which at current levels
would render it one of the 35 most highly capitalised UK companies.
BT added 4 up at 380p as the market buzzed with talk of an immiment disposal
of the group's 35.9m share stake in AT&amp;T following the US telecom group's
filing of a registration statement. The disposal could bring in some Dollars
1.7bn at current prices. Turnover in BT was 8.7m shares.
Retailer Great Universal Stores surprised the market with a special 30p
dividend with its interim profits. The shares closed at 496p xd after active
trading of 4.3m.
The move followed weeks of market speculation suggesting the company would
use part of its cash mountain of around Pounds 1.5bn to launch a share
buy-back scheme.
The one-off special payment made yesterday will cost around Pounds 300m,
still leaving the group with some Pounds 1.2bn and prompted speculation that
GUS may soon make another or even go for the much predicted share buy-back
option.
Half-time profits at Pounds 225m, against Pounds 213.2m a year earlier, came
in below market forecasts. BZW downgraded full-year expectations by 3 per
cent to Pounds 555m, saying its move reflected 'the weakness in the clothing
market and recalculation of the interest charge'. UBS cut its full-year
prediction by Pounds 10m to Pounds 575m.
Takeover enthusiasm fuelled the financials area as analysts and investors
looked towards a fundamental shakeout. Kleinwort Benson jumped 32 to 522p.
Smith New Court, where profits were above expectations but still down 35 per
cent, improved 23 to 396p - many expect the classic market-maker to attract
a bid.
Schroders moved 40 higher to 1460p and MAM, Warburg's 75 per cent-owned fund
management arm, leapt 39 to 653p.
Technical pressure was behind a retreat of 7 to 426p in British Aerospace,
rather than any rethink on Wednesday's monopolies referral for the bids from
both BAe and GEC for submarine maker VSEL, which dipped 2 to 1336p. GEC was
steady ahead of today's interim results at 275p.
Yesterday's increase in duty on alcohol by the UK chancellor brought a
retreat in several stocks in the sector. Whitbread gave up 6 to 553p and
Guinness a penny to 438p. Bass relinquished a penny to 518p, with sentiment
further hurt by a sell recommendation from NatWest Securities.
Electronics group Racal tumbled 13 to 203p in 4.9m turnover as analysts
found clear signs of margins pressure in the interim statement and promptly
downgraded full-year profits estimates. NatWest Securities came down by
Pounds 5m to Pounds 60m but found the shares attractive at present levels,
against a net asset value of close to 190p.
The reawakening of bid fever, prompted by the Warburg situation, spread like
a virus and marketmakers were soon rounding up the usual suspects. It was
harder to see a stronger rationale for stories that Glaxo was sharpening its
claws for either Wellcome or Zeneca. But all three ended brighter on the
day, Glaxo up 8 to 629p, Wellcome 10 to 675p and Zeneca 11 to 847p.
Carlton Communications fell 10 in early dealing on worries over derivatives
trading. When it was realised that the figure was minimal and Carlton was
suing Bankers Trust rather than the other way round, the stock rebounded to
close 4 ahead on balance at 872p.
An acquisition, rights issue and promise of higher profits and dividends
this year left motor distributor and bus operator Cowie 6 higher at 224p in
1.1m turnover. The rights issue will bring in some Pounds 33m, half of which
will finance the purchase of the group's second London bus operation. News
of the extra equity was sweetened by a forecast 16 per cent increase in
dividends for 1994.
Refractories maker Hewitt soared 60 to 158p as the group unveiled plans for
an injection of new capital and management.
Stores group Kingfisher declined 7 to 427p after BZW downgraded profits
expectations. The investment bank reduced its current year prediction by
Pounds 15m to Pounds 315m to take account of 'trading difficulties at
Woolworths (its high street subsidiary) and a higher than expected interest
charge'.
A recommendation from Kleinwort Benson boosted Ladbroke, 4 firmer at 162p.
Disappointing interim figures from Fine Art Developments, along with a
cautious outlook on the second half, saw the shares slide 44 to 376p.
Other statistics, Page 37
