<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / London Stock Exchange: Warburg bid war starts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and JEFFREY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The merchant bank sector was set alight with news that SG Warburg and big US
investment bank Morgan Stanley were in merger talks.
Speculation had been smouldering for some time, although it had focused on
US rival JP Morgan. Yesterday it flared up, prompting a Stock Exchange
announcement that share prices shown on dealing screens were merely
indicative.
An hour of intense upside pressure saw Warburg shares up 146p at their best
and forced the UK merchant bank to announce that it was in talks.
'Warburg has just bought itself into play and this one's going through the
roof,' said one dealer. 'It could go to Pounds 12 or Pounds 15.'
Many saw it as the opening of an auction that could include banks such as
Dresdner, of Germany. Credit Lyonnais Laing said: 'It is a once in a decade
event when a leading financial institution in the UK puts its hands up and
effectively says it would be better off as part of a larger group.' The
house would not comment on its valuations but rivals said it was talking of
an ultimate figure as high as Pounds 16.
James Capel believes a US bank such as JP Morgan might enter the fray,
perhaps because it merely wants to see the exit price bid higher but also
because it has previously expressed an interest.
Warburg shares closed 119 up at 791p on turnover of 10m, the second most
active volume recorded in the stock. Morgan Stanley was trading Dollars 1
higher at Dollars 57 7/8 in New York as London closed.
UBS, however, takes a more downbeat view. It believes that any merger will
run into big regulatory problems and a rival bidder is unlikely.
</TEXT>
